{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/534"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"534"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53680"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"759"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"253"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22736"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44467"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68223","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68223"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents to a small rural hospital with a 24 hour history of increasing pain in her right groin. The patient is thin and the landmarks in her groin are easy to identify. There is an exquisitely tender 2 cm fixed swelling below and lateral to the pubic tubercle. The swelling is deep to the skin. The examination of her abdomen, external genitalia and lower limbs is otherwise normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ultrasound of the groin","Fine needle aspiration cytology","Fine needle aspiration for culture","Incision and drainage","Surgical exploration"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe anatomical site of the swelling is clearly defined. The swelling is tender and fixed - ie it cannot be reduced. This patient has a strangulated femoral hernia. No further investigations are required. She needs \u003Cstrong\u003Esurgical intervention\u003C/strong\u003E. Any form of imaging will be superfluous. Point-of-care ultrasound can be used by a trained operator in the Emergency Department to provide further information - but these facilities might not be available in a small rural hospital. Ultrasonography is used increasingly in the assessment of subcutaneous swellings. If the patient is obese and the swelling difficult to define, such an approach would be reasonable. However, in this case a clear anatomical description is provided and there should be little doubt as to the diagnosis - an incarcerated and strangulated femoral hernia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the swelling involved skin, the underlying problem might be one of infection and abscess formation, where aspiration for culture or incision and drainage of pus might be appropriate - but that would be a hazardous undertaking in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tenderness over an incarcerated abdominal wall hernia implies strangulation of the contents of the hernia."],"references":["Fitzgibbons RJ, Forse RA. Groin Hernias in Adults. N Eng J Med 2015; 372:756-63."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53680"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"534"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53680","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53680"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T15:20:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T15:21:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"534"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68223"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"